{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c80368ee-a3e1-4cf3-863a-a97be2bf3dce","content":"In .NET 10 MAUI, the iOS-specific `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` was replaced with a **cross-platform** `Page.SafeAreaRegions` property.\n\n**Old (.NET 9):**\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\">\n```\n\n**New (.NET 10):**\n```xml\n<ContentPage SafeAreaRegions=\"All\">\n```\n\nYou can drop the `xmlns:ios` declaration entirely (if it was only used for this). The `SafeAreaRegions` values are:\n\n| Value | Effect |\n|-------|--------|\n| `All` | Insets content from all safe area edges (status bar, notch, home indicator) |\n| `None` | No safe area insets (edge-to-edge) |\n| `Top`, `Bottom`, `Left`, `Right` | Individual edges (combinable) |\n\nSince `All` is the default in .NET 10, your content *should* already be inset — if it isn't, explicitly set it and make sure no parent layout is overriding the padding.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d9e22565-e568-4fdf-92b9-3ee519936b92","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET MAUI migration issue from .NET 9 to .NET 10 regarding safe area handling on iOS. This is a known breaking change in .NET 10 MAUI.\n\nIn .NET 10, the `UseSafeArea` attached property was removed/changed. The new approach uses `SafeAreaRegions` on the `Page` level.\n\nLet me provide the correct answer based on my knowledge of .NET MAUI .NET 10 changes.\n\nIn .NET 10 MAUI, `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` was replaced with a cross-platform `Page.SafeAreaRegions` property. \n\nThe `SafeAreaRegions` property accepts values like `All` (the default, equivalent to the old `UseSafeArea=\"True\"`), `None`, or individual regions like `Top`, `Bottom`, `Left`, and `Right` that can be combined.\n\nSince the user's content is appearing behind the status bar in .NET 10, the old iOS-specific `UseSafeArea` property likely isn't being respected anymore — it's been replaced by this cross-platform approach. I should show them how to set `SafeAreaRegions` in XAML to properly inset the content away from the safe areas.\n\nWriting XAML example...","outputTokens":958,"requestId":"0436:2086DF:13D473E:1631FE7:6A027CE6"},"id":"34b503b9-8833-45d9-8383-721dbb744931","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:06:03.580Z","parentId":"d6948850-6d81-4635-a28d-7c33c9d5bff3"}
